<br>
A high-level pally can do much better than what Tseng said in terms of healing.  Just ask Jilhome and Jedicat.  I grouped with them in different occasions in recent weeks.  They are all honorable Pallies.  In Karnor's Castle, when we cannot find a healer (no druid and shaman in the group, let alone cleric), I tried one-pally-one-ranger format as the group healers 3 times and we are still doing fine.  The reason?  Pally is decent in healing and better than what a ranger can do (not even counting the magic from DW helm).  They gave what they have without reservation.<br>
<br>
A player who is considerate to his teammates will not only earn respect but also gain trust from other players.  This especially applies to the Pally who is generous to LOH others.  Do I mind if a Pally doesn't cast LOH on others?  No I don't.  Do I trust more to those pallies who are generous?  Yes.  Am I willing to invite them as long as I am the group leader and have a spot?  You bet.  I beleive many players think the samw way as I do in regard to this.<br>
<br>
Trustworthiness and reliability, not really skills, are in fact the most valuable assets in EQ.  They can carry you along the long journey.<br>
